The ``collections.abc`` module includes Abstract Base Classes that require only little customisation. [``collections.abc.MutableSequence``][1] is the ABC closest to a ``list`` - you have to override ``__delitem__``, ``__getitem__``, ``__setitem__``, ``__len__``, and ``insert``. Other magic methods, such as ``__iter__``, will use these as required.



    class MyList(collections.abc.MutableSequence):
        def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
            self._data = list(*args, **kwargs)

        def __len__(self):
            return len(self._data)

        def __delitem__(self, item):
            del self._data[item]

        def __getitem__(self, item):
            return self._data[item]

        def __setitem__(self, item, value):
            self._data[item] = value

        def insert(self, i, x):
            self._data.insert(i, x)


  [1]: https://docs.python.org/3/library/collections.abc.html#collections.abc.MutableSequence

